<subSubSection id="D4E0654CFFF1FD07FF700994B69BFEAE" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="55" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" type="description">
<paragraph id="9C4536C7FFF1FD08FF700994B35CFE38" blockId="7.[151,595,431,492]" box="[151,368,466,492]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">
(
<figureCitation id="04C12A42FFF1FD08FF780994B2DDFE38" box="[159,241,466,492]" captionStart="PLATE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,238,1874,1898]" captionTargetBox="[227,1352,205,1841]" captionTargetId="figure-85@3.[215,1357,197,1841]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="PLATE 1 (haenschi and sophorae) 1. Brassolis haenschi haenschi female ECUADOR: Normandia, BMNH. 2. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas ZMUC. 3. Brassolis sophorae luridus Holotype male, COLOMBIA: Río Magdalena, BMNH. 4. Brassolis sophorae philomela Paralectotype female, ECUADOR: Macas, BMNH. 5. Brassolis sophorae philomela Lectotype male, ECUADOR: Macas, BMNH. 6. Brassolis sophorae ardens female, Peru La Union, BMNH. 7. Brassolis sophorae ardens Lectotype male, PERU: Pozuzo, BMNH." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5125053" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5125053/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Plate 1</figureCitation>
, figs. 3–7)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C4536C7FFF1FD08FF700A64B31CFDB0" blockId="7.[151,1436,546,2012]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">
Three taxa, all named by Stichel (
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FDCB0A64B0F1FDEF" box="[556,733,546,571]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">luridus, ardens</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FCFE0A64B1A2FDEF" box="[793,910,546,571]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">philomela</emphasis>
) have been linked to 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFF1FD08FB740A64B72CFDEF" box="[1171,1280,546,571]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sophorae">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FB740A64B72CFDEF" box="[1171,1280,546,571]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">sophorae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry id="E4ED7657FFF1FD08FACF0A64B7B7FDE8" box="[1320,1435,546,572]" name="Colombia" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Colombia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="E4ED7657FFF1FD08FF2F0A0CB300FDB0" box="[200,300,586,612]" name="Ecuador" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C4536C7FFF1FD08FF210A34B35BFB97" blockId="7.[151,1436,546,2012]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">
The description of 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFF1FD08FE540A34B089FD5F" box="[435,677,626,651]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="sophorae" subSpecies="luridus">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FE540A34B089FD5F" box="[435,677,626,651]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">B. sophorae luridus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was based on 
<specimenCount id="8AFCFD4EFFF1FD08FC830A34B1FFFD58" box="[868,979,626,652]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" type="male">one male</specimenCount>
in Stichel’s collection (
<bibRefCitation id="F86B4B36FFF1FD08FB1C0A34B7BBFD58" author="Stichel, H." box="[1275,1431,626,652]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" pagination="487 - 524" refId="ref6087" refString="Stichel, H. (1902) Aufteilung der Gattung Opsiphanes West., Beschreibung neuer Brassoliden und synonymische Notizen. Berliner entomologische Zeitschrift, 46, 487 - 524." type="journal article" year="1902">Stichel 1902</bibRefCitation>
, p.520). In the Rothschild Collection in the BMNH there is a male with a printed label ‘ 
<collectingCountry id="E4ED7657FFF1FD08FB140ADCB742FD60" box="[1267,1390,666,692]" name="Colombia" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, R. Magdalana [sic] s e.c. Stichel’, a handwritten ‘ 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFF1FD08FD5A0A84B1CAFD08" authority="Stich." authorityName="Stich." box="[701,998,706,732]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="sophorae" subSpecies="lurida">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FD5A0A84B1B6FD0F" box="[701,922,706,731]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">B. sophorae lurida</emphasis>
Stich.
</taxonomicName>
Type’, a round, red-margined, ‘type’ label, and a red, rectangular, ‘Typus’ label. This is regarded as the 
<typeStatus id="43418865FFF1FD08FC4E0AACB63CFCD0" box="[937,1040,746,772]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation id="04C12A42FFF1FD08FBF80AACB65EFCD0" box="[1055,1138,746,772]" captionStart="PLATE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,238,1874,1898]" captionTargetBox="[227,1352,205,1841]" captionTargetId="figure-85@3.[215,1357,197,1841]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="PLATE 1 (haenschi and sophorae) 1. Brassolis haenschi haenschi female ECUADOR: Normandia, BMNH. 2. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas ZMUC. 3. Brassolis sophorae luridus Holotype male, COLOMBIA: Río Magdalena, BMNH. 4. Brassolis sophorae philomela Paralectotype female, ECUADOR: Macas, BMNH. 5. Brassolis sophorae philomela Lectotype male, ECUADOR: Macas, BMNH. 6. Brassolis sophorae ardens female, Peru La Union, BMNH. 7. Brassolis sophorae ardens Lectotype male, PERU: Pozuzo, BMNH." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5125053" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5125053/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Plate 1</figureCitation>
, fig. 3). As stated above, 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFF1FD08FF700B54B328FCFF" box="[151,260,786,811]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sophorae">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FF700B54B328FCFF" box="[151,260,786,811]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">sophorae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not appear to occur in the 
<collectingRegion id="5E3EF825FFF1FD08FD9D0B54B0D0FCF8" box="[634,764,786,812]" country="Colombia" name="Magdalena" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Magdalena</collectingRegion>
Valley and the type is probably from the Colombian Oriente. The forewing band of type 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FDF30B7CB04BFC87" box="[532,615,826,851]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">luridus</emphasis>
is more yellow than most Colombian specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFF1FD08FB230B7CB71DFC87" box="[1220,1329,826,851]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sophorae">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FB230B7CB71DFC87" box="[1220,1329,826,851]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">sophorae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Oriente (but matched by one from 
<collectingRegion id="5E3EF825FFF1FD08FDCC0B24B0B0FCA8" box="[555,668,866,892]" country="Colombia" name="Casanare" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Casanare</collectingRegion>
); the two spots at the apex of the forewing cell are well developed (also seen in the 
<collectingRegion id="5E3EF825FFF1FD08FE870BCCB3E7FC70" box="[352,459,906,932]" country="Colombia" name="Casanare" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Casanare</collectingRegion>
specimen), the hindwing band is narrower (but matched by one from Mocoa) and less distinct (but matched by a specimen from Leticia). Thus, type 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FC520BF4B624FC1F" box="[949,1032,946,971]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">luridus</emphasis>
does not differ significantly from specimens of Colombian 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFF1FD08FE240B9CB01CFC27" box="[451,560,986,1011]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sophorae">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FE240B9CB01CFC27" box="[451,560,986,1011]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">sophorae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Oriente, which in turn are similar to 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FBB20B9CB6E6FC27" box="[1109,1226,986,1011]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">philomela</emphasis>
(see below) from the Ecuadorian Oriente. I regard these two taxa as one, for which the name 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FBEF0C44B677FBCF" box="[1032,1115,1026,1051]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">luridus</emphasis>
has priority, and 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FAC00C44B7B0FBCF" box="[1319,1436,1026,1051]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">philomela</emphasis>
falls as a synonym.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C4536C7FFF1FD08FF210C14B6FCFB40" blockId="7.[151,1436,546,2012]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">
Initially (
<bibRefCitation id="F86B4B36FFF1FD08FED50C14B3E4FBB8" author="Stichel, H" box="[306,456,1106,1132]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" pagination="244" refId="ref6146" refString="Stichel, H .. (1909) Brassolidae. Das Tierreich, 25, xiv, 244." type="journal article" year="1909">Stichel 1909</bibRefCitation>
, p.13), Ecuadorian specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFF1FD08FCAC0C15B194FBB8" box="[843,952,1107,1132]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sophorae">
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FCAC0C15B194FBB8" box="[843,952,1107,1132]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">sophorae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Oriente were grouped with subspecies 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FF140C3DB36EFB40" box="[243,322,1147,1172]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">ardens</emphasis>
Stichel from 
<collectingCountry id="E4ED7657FFF1FD08FE060C3CB035FB40" box="[481,537,1146,1172]" name="Peru" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Peru</collectingCountry>
, but later (
<bibRefCitation id="F86B4B36FFF1FD08FD720C3CB100FB40" author="Stichel, H." box="[661,812,1146,1172]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" pagination="61 - 69" refId="ref6164" refString="Stichel, H. (1925) Zur Systematik der Brassolidae (Lep. Rhop.). Neue Beitrage zur systematischen Insektenkunde, 3 (8 / 9), 61 - 69." type="journal article" year="1925">Stichel 1925</bibRefCitation>
, p.60), they were named 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FBB30C3DB6E5FB40" box="[1108,1225,1147,1172]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">philomela</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C4536C7FFF1FD08FF210CE4B7A3F998" blockId="7.[151,1436,546,2012]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">
The description of 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FE430CE5B3DFFB68" box="[420,499,1187,1212]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">ardens</emphasis>
was based on 
<specimenCount id="8AFCFD4EFFF1FD08FD7B0CE4B124FB68" box="[668,776,1186,1212]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" type="male">two male</specimenCount>
<typeStatus id="43418865FFF1FD08FCE80CE4B159FB68" box="[783,885,1186,1212]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">syntypes</typeStatus>
from ‘ 
<collectingCountry id="E4ED7657FFF1FD08FC250CE4B1D1FB68" box="[962,1021,1186,1212]" name="Peru" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Peru</collectingCountry>
merid. (Chanchamayo) i. coll. Thieme, Berlin et mea, leg. W. Hoffmanns’. In selecting one of these as 
<typeStatus id="43418865FFF1FD08FC300C8CB669FB30" box="[983,1093,1226,1252]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">lectotype</typeStatus>
, there is a slight problem. A male figured by 
<bibRefCitation id="F86B4B36FFF1FD08FEBA0CB4B020FAD8" author="Stichel, H." box="[349,524,1266,1292]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" pagination="1 - 48" refId="ref6118" refString="Stichel, H. (1904 b) Lepidoptera Rhopalocera. Fam. Nymphalidae. Subfam. Brassolinae. Genera Insectorum, 20, 1 - 48." type="journal article" year="1904">Stichel (1904b</bibRefCitation>
, pl 3., fig. 1) was not designated a type, but it could be the 
<typeStatus id="43418865FFF1FD08FB3C0CB4B71AFAD8" box="[1243,1334,1266,1292]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">syntype</typeStatus>
in ‘coll. Thieme’. In this same article, 
<bibRefCitation id="F86B4B36FFF1FD08FE190D5CB082FAE0" author="Stichel, H." box="[510,686,1306,1332]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" pagination="1 - 48" refId="ref6118" refString="Stichel, H. (1904 b) Lepidoptera Rhopalocera. Fam. Nymphalidae. Subfam. Brassolinae. Genera Insectorum, 20, 1 - 48." type="journal article" year="1904">Stichel (1904b</bibRefCitation>
, p.7) changed the collecting locality to ‘Süd Peru’. A different male in the Rothschild Collection has a round, red-margined, ‘Type’ label, a red, rectangular Typus label, a printed rectangular label ‘Süd 
<collectingCountry id="E4ED7657FFF1FD08FDEB0D2CB069FA50" box="[524,581,1386,1412]" name="Peru" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Peru</collectingCountry>
, Pozuzo, e.c. H. Stichel’, and a handwritten ‘ 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FB9F0D2DB761FA50" box="[1144,1357,1387,1412]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">
<taxonomicName id="5BFA4D44FFF1FD08FB9F0D2DB6C3FA50" box="[1144,1263,1387,1412]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sophor">B. sophor</taxonomicName>
. ardens
</emphasis>
Stich. Cotype’. Whenever Stichel had several specimens in a type series, he appeared to regard one, to which he fixed a handwritten determination, as 
<typeStatus id="43418865FFF1FD08FD8C0DFCB0F8FA00" box="[619,724,1466,1492]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">holotype</typeStatus>
, and the others (which simply bear red ‘typus’ labels) as 
<typeStatus id="43418865FFF1FD08FF700DA4B327FA28" box="[151,267,1506,1532]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">paratypes</typeStatus>
. He never formally designated 
<typeStatus id="43418865FFF1FD08FD9D0DA4B0C3FA28" box="[634,751,1506,1532]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">holotypes</typeStatus>
, but, with one exception, I have always (
<bibRefCitation id="F86B4B36FFF1FD08FB370DA4B755FA28" author="Bristow, C. R." box="[1232,1401,1506,1532]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" pagination="203 - 293" refId="ref5891" refString="Bristow, C. R. (1991) A revision of the brassoline genus Opsiphanes (Lepidoptera: Rhopalocera). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 101, 203 - 293." type="journal article" year="1991">Bristow, 1991</bibRefCitation>
, p. 206 and references therein) selected as 
<typeStatus id="43418865FFF1FD08FD640E4CB0C2F9F0" box="[643,750,1546,1572]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">lectotype</typeStatus>
in each case, the specimen with the handwritten label. Despite the slight discrepancy in locality data, the above male has been designated 
<typeStatus id="43418865FFF1FD08FB820E74B6FCF998" box="[1125,1232,1586,1612]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">lectotype</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation id="04C12A42FFF1FD08FB070E74B71EF998" box="[1248,1330,1586,1612]" captionStart="PLATE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,238,1874,1898]" captionTargetBox="[227,1352,205,1841]" captionTargetId="figure-85@3.[215,1357,197,1841]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="PLATE 1 (haenschi and sophorae) 1. Brassolis haenschi haenschi female ECUADOR: Normandia, BMNH. 2. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas ZMUC. 3. Brassolis sophorae luridus Holotype male, COLOMBIA: Río Magdalena, BMNH. 4. Brassolis sophorae philomela Paralectotype female, ECUADOR: Macas, BMNH. 5. Brassolis sophorae philomela Lectotype male, ECUADOR: Macas, BMNH. 6. Brassolis sophorae ardens female, Peru La Union, BMNH. 7. Brassolis sophorae ardens Lectotype male, PERU: Pozuzo, BMNH." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5125053" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5125053/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Plate 1</figureCitation>
, fig. 7).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C4536C7FFF1FD08FF210E1CB02CF8E8" blockId="7.[151,1436,546,2012]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">
The description of 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FE420E1DB036F9A0" box="[421,538,1627,1652]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">philomela</emphasis>
appears to have been based on 
<specimenCount id="8AFCFD4EFFF1FD08FC690E1CB1D5F9A0" box="[910,1017,1626,1652]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" type="male">one male</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount id="8AFCFD4EFFF1FD08FBD50E1CB698F9A0" box="[1074,1204,1626,1652]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" type="female">one female</specimenCount>
from Macas, 
<collectingCountry id="E4ED7657FFF1FD08FABF0E1CB2ECF948" name="Ecuador" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
. A male in the Rothschild Collection with a round, red-margined, ‘Type’ label, a rectangular red ‘Typus’ label, a white printed ‘Macas, Ecuador’ label, and a handwritten ‘ 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FC7D0EEDB665F910" box="[922,1097,1707,1732]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">B. s. philomela</emphasis>
Stich.’ is designated the 
<typeStatus id="43418865FFF1FD08FA970EECB2CCF938" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">lectotype</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation id="04C12A42FFF1FD08FF080E94B36DF938" box="[239,321,1746,1772]" captionStart="PLATE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,238,1874,1898]" captionTargetBox="[227,1352,205,1841]" captionTargetId="figure-85@3.[215,1357,197,1841]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="PLATE 1 (haenschi and sophorae) 1. Brassolis haenschi haenschi female ECUADOR: Normandia, BMNH. 2. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas ZMUC. 3. Brassolis sophorae luridus Holotype male, COLOMBIA: Río Magdalena, BMNH. 4. Brassolis sophorae philomela Paralectotype female, ECUADOR: Macas, BMNH. 5. Brassolis sophorae philomela Lectotype male, ECUADOR: Macas, BMNH. 6. Brassolis sophorae ardens female, Peru La Union, BMNH. 7. Brassolis sophorae ardens Lectotype male, PERU: Pozuzo, BMNH." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5125053" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5125053/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Plate 1</figureCitation>
, fig.5). There is also a female with a red rectangular ‘Typus’ label and a printed ‘Macas, Ecuador’ which is regarded as a 
<typeStatus id="43418865FFF1FD08FE3D0EBCB054F8C0" box="[474,632,1786,1812]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">paralectotype</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation id="04C12A42FFF1FD08FD610EBCB0F5F8C0" box="[646,729,1786,1812]" captionStart="PLATE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,238,1874,1898]" captionTargetBox="[227,1352,205,1841]" captionTargetId="figure-85@3.[215,1357,197,1841]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="PLATE 1 (haenschi and sophorae) 1. Brassolis haenschi haenschi female ECUADOR: Normandia, BMNH. 2. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas ZMUC. 3. Brassolis sophorae luridus Holotype male, COLOMBIA: Río Magdalena, BMNH. 4. Brassolis sophorae philomela Paralectotype female, ECUADOR: Macas, BMNH. 5. Brassolis sophorae philomela Lectotype male, ECUADOR: Macas, BMNH. 6. Brassolis sophorae ardens female, Peru La Union, BMNH. 7. Brassolis sophorae ardens Lectotype male, PERU: Pozuzo, BMNH." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5125053" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5125053/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Plate 1</figureCitation>
, fig.4). However, as stated above, 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FB890EBDB6CFF8C0" box="[1134,1251,1787,1812]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">philomela</emphasis>
, new synonym, is a junior synonym of 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FE410F65B02CF8E8" box="[422,512,1827,1852]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">luridus.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C4536C7FFF1FD08FF210F0CB1F6F858" blockId="7.[151,1436,546,2012]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">
The difference between 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FE060F0DB01CF8B0" box="[481,560,1867,1892]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">ardens</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FD8F0F0DB097F8B0" box="[616,699,1867,1892]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">luridus</emphasis>
is not absolutely clear-cut, but a combination of at least two of the following features appear to be diagnostic. In both sexes of 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FC990F35B1FDF858" box="[894,977,1907,1932]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">luridus</emphasis>
:
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C4536C7FFF1FD08FF700FDCB73AF860" blockId="7.[151,1436,546,2012]" box="[151,1302,1946,1972]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">
1) the forewing band only just enters the space below vein 2a (much better developed in 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFF1FD08FB510FDDB729F860" box="[1206,1285,1947,1972]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">ardens</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C4536C7FFF1FD08FF700F84B7B0F808" blockId="7.[151,1436,546,2012]" box="[151,1436,1986,2012]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">2) generally, the hindwing band is not so well developed (there are several exceptions, but the widest bands</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C4536C7FFFEFD07FF2408DEB662FF66" blockId="8.[151,1102,152,298]" box="[195,1102,152,178]" pageId="8" pageNumber="55">
are confined to specimens of 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFEFD07FDFC08DEB046FF65" box="[539,618,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="55">ardens</emphasis>
, and the least well developed to 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFEFD07FC0D08DEB611FF65" box="[1002,1085,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="55">luridus</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C4536C7FFFEFD07FF210886B3ADFF0E" blockId="8.[151,1102,152,298]" box="[198,385,192,218]" pageId="8" pageNumber="55">
In male 
<emphasis id="AE8EEAD5FFFEFD07FEC10886B355FF0D" box="[294,377,192,217]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="55">luridus</emphasis>
:
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C4536C7FFFEFD07FF7008AEB1E0FED6" blockId="8.[151,1102,152,298]" box="[151,972,232,258]" pageId="8" pageNumber="55">1) the forewing band is usually confined to the upper part of the cell.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C4536C7FFFEFD07FF700956B1C3FEFE" blockId="8.[151,1102,152,298]" box="[151,1007,272,298]" pageId="8" pageNumber="55">2) one, commonly two, co-joined spots at apex of cell better developed.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C4536C7FFFEFD07FF210926B69BFEAE" blockId="8.[198,1207,352,378]" box="[198,1207,352,378]" pageId="8" pageNumber="55">
The 
<typeStatus id="43418865FFFEFD07FF1C0926B34DFEAE" box="[251,353,352,378]" pageId="8" pageNumber="55">holotype</typeStatus>
measures 
<quantity id="5B029B22FFFEFD07FE3A0926B01FFEAE" box="[477,563,352,378]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.1" pageId="8" pageNumber="55" unit="mm" value="41.0">41 mm</quantity>
; female forewing length varies from 
<quantity id="5B029B22FFFEFD07FC020926B61AFEAE" box="[997,1078,352,378]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.8" pageId="8" pageNumber="55" unit="mm" value="48.0">48 mm</quantity>
to 
<quantity id="5B029B22FFFEFD07FBBB0926B69EFEAE" box="[1116,1202,352,378]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.7" pageId="8" pageNumber="55" unit="mm" value="57.0">57 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
